tweets.text: @sarahjolly1 @MyWakefield @EnvAgency I don’t think it is fly tipping. It’s by the canal at Stanley Ferry marina - I think it’s been brought there by the flood water and as it’s subsided, been left high and dry. You can see the dead vegetation trapped in the metal ‘rungs’ of the foot bridge. It looks terrible.

@HilaryMilburn @MyWakefield There was one area where the water had gone round an island bit and the stagnant water was grey, cloudy and soapy looking. Not sure if fly tipping in a river is a @MyWakefield  or @EnvAgency issue

We are working with contractors to remove floating pennywort from the river Lark on the Great Ouse. 
 
Pennywort is an invasive foreign species which grows prolifically damaging the river ecosystem, harming wildlife and preventing boating and angling. #Boats #Cambridgeshire https://t.co/JKCTS5Ha3Y
